1
00:00:00,080 --> 00:00:04,730
In this video we are going to learn the benefits of microservices.

2
00:00:05,060 --> 00:00:10,460
As we already talked on previous video, but let's elaborate these benefits one by one.

3
00:00:10,490 --> 00:00:15,050
The first benefit is agility, innovation and time to market.

4
00:00:15,410 --> 00:00:21,890
Microservice architecture make applications easier to scale and faster to develop, enabling innovation

5
00:00:21,890 --> 00:00:24,680
and accelerating time to market for new features.

6
00:00:24,710 --> 00:00:31,190
Since microservices are smaller and independently deployable, it is easier to manage bug fixes and

7
00:00:31,190 --> 00:00:32,479
feature releases.

8
00:00:32,960 --> 00:00:38,750
You can update a service without redeploying the entire application and rollback an update if something

9
00:00:38,750 --> 00:00:39,680
goes wrong.

10
00:00:39,890 --> 00:00:46,010
In monolithic applications, if a bug is found in one part of the application, it can block the entire

11
00:00:46,010 --> 00:00:47,240
release process.

12
00:00:47,240 --> 00:00:53,510
So new features was waiting for a bug fix to be integrated, tested and published in microservices.

13
00:00:55,110 --> 00:00:58,200
Second benefit is flexible scalability.

14
00:00:58,320 --> 00:01:06,000
Microservices can be scaled independently so you can scale out sub services that require less resources

15
00:01:06,000 --> 00:01:08,850
without scaling out the entire application.

16
00:01:08,850 --> 00:01:15,480
So we can say that microservices require less infrastructure than monolithic applications because they

17
00:01:15,480 --> 00:01:21,870
enable precise scaling of only the required services instead of scaling the entire application.

18
00:01:21,870 --> 00:01:29,550
Also, scaling is very easy with using an container orchestration tool like Kubernetes, we can pack

19
00:01:29,550 --> 00:01:35,730
a higher volume of the services onto a single host, which allows for more efficient utilization of

20
00:01:35,730 --> 00:01:37,230
hardware resources.

21
00:01:38,640 --> 00:01:41,580
Another benefit is small focused teams.

22
00:01:41,580 --> 00:01:47,850
Microservices should be small enough that a single featured team can build, test, and deploy it.

23
00:01:47,850 --> 00:01:54,510
The microservice model enables an organization to create small cross-functional teams around one service

24
00:01:54,510 --> 00:01:59,670
or a collection of microservices, and have them operate in agile fashion.

25
00:01:59,670 --> 00:02:02,460
Small team size increases the agility.

26
00:02:02,460 --> 00:02:09,509
Large teams tend to be less productive due to communication is slower and management overhead goes up.

27
00:02:09,509 --> 00:02:16,410
So that occurs the agility diminishing, so small teams and focused teams provided by microservices.

28
00:02:16,530 --> 00:02:19,920
Another benefit is small and separated codebase.

29
00:02:19,920 --> 00:02:24,540
In monolithic application, the codebase is going to be so bigger over time.

30
00:02:24,540 --> 00:02:28,110
For code dependencies to become tangled, try to.

31
00:02:28,110 --> 00:02:32,340
Adding any feature requires lots of refactoring on existing code base.

32
00:02:32,340 --> 00:02:39,600
Since microservices are not sharing code or data stores with other services, it minimizes dependencies

33
00:02:39,600 --> 00:02:42,450
and that makes it easier to adding new features.

